  "@graph": [
    {
      "@id": "M0_Ptoe.jsonld",
      "@type": "owl:Ontology",
      "rdfs:label": "Periodic Table of Elements (Ptoe)",
      "rdfs:comment": "TSCG instance modeling the Periodic Table of the Elements as a transdisciplinary organizational system. The table encodes the relationship between atomic structure (electron configuration) and chemical properties through a hierarchical spatial arrangement. It demonstrates how quantum mechanical constraints (Pauli principle, Aufbau rule) generate emergent periodic patterns in electronegativity, atomic radius, ionization energy, and reactivity across 118 elements organized in 7 periods, 18 groups, and 4 orbital blocks (s, p, d, f).",
      "m3:ontologyType": {
        "@id": "m3:Poclet"
      },
      "m1:domain": "Chemistry",
      "owl:versionInfo": "1.0.0",
      "owl:imports": [
        "M3_GenesisSpace.jsonld",
        "M2_GenericConcepts.jsonld",
        "M1_CoreConcepts.jsonld",
        "M1_extensions/chemistry/M1_Chemistry.jsonld"
      ],
      "dcterms:created": "2026-04-26",
      "dcterms:creator": "Echopraxium with the collaboration of Claude AI",
      "m2:changelog": [
        {
          "version": "1.0.0",
          "date": "2026-04-26",
          "description": "Initial creation. TSCG instance modeling the Periodic Table of Elements with bicephalous ASFID/REVOI scoring, 19 M2 GenericConcepts mobilized across 6 families (10 Structural, 4 Informational, 3 Ontological, 2 Regulatory), epistemic gap δ₁≈0.057 (OnCriticalLine spectral class)."
        }
      ],
      "m0:completeness": "complete",
      "m0:completenessJustification": "All 5 ASFID dimensions are represented: A (noble gas attractors), S (periodic grid + block structure), F (property gradients), I (electron configuration encoding), D (radioactive decay, phase transitions). The system is closed (118 elements, bounded by atomic number Z).",
      "m0:minimality": "minimal",
      "m0:minimalityJustification": "118 elements are the minimal set to represent the periodic structure (cannot remove any without losing completeness). The 4 blocks (s, p, d, f) are the minimal orbital classification. The grid topology is the minimal representation preserving both period and group relationships.",
      "m0:pedagogy": "high",
      "m0:pedagogyJustification": "The Periodic Table is universally taught in secondary and tertiary education worldwide. It serves as the foundational framework for chemistry, materials science, and chemical engineering. Visualization is iconic and immediately recognizable.",
      "m0:observer": "Chemistry/Physics scientist or student",
      "m0:observerPerspective": "The table is constructed from a quantum mechanical observer perspective (Schrödinger equation, Pauli principle) and empirical observation (spectroscopy, reactivity experiments). The arrangement prioritizes chemical similarity (groups) and electronic structure (periods/blocks).",
      "m0:asfidScores": {
        "A": 0.85,
        "S": 0.90,
        "F": 0.70,
        "I": 0.95,
        "D": 0.65,
        "mean": 0.81
      },
      "m0:revoiScores": {
        "R": 0.95,
        "E": 0.80,
        "V": 0.95,
        "O": 0.90,
        "I": 0.85,
        "mean": 0.89
      },
      "components": [
        {
          "@id": "m0:Ptoe:Elements",
          "@type": "m2:Component",
          "rdfs:label": "118 Chemical Elements",
          "rdfs:comment": "The complete set of known chemical elements from Hydrogen (Z=1) to Oganesson (Z=118). Each element is uniquely defined by its atomic number Z (number of protons) and has a distinct electron configuration, chemical symbol, and set of physical/chemical properties.",
          "m1:instanceOf": "m1.ext:chemistry:Element",
          "m0:cardinality": 118,
          "m0:examples": [
            "H (Hydrogen, Z=1): 1s¹, lightest element, fuel in stars",
            "C (Carbon, Z=6): [He] 2s² 2p², basis of organic chemistry",
            "Fe (Iron, Z=26): [Ar] 3d⁶ 4s², most abundant transition metal in Earth's crust",
            "Au (Gold, Z=79): [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s¹, noble metal, high electronegativity",
            "Og (Oganesson, Z=118): [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² 7p⁶, superheavy noble gas (predicted)"
          ],
          "asfidContribution": {
            "A": 0.75,
            "S": 0.90,
            "F": 0.65,
            "I": 0.95,
            "D": 0.60
          }
        },
        {
          "@id": "m0:Ptoe:PeriodicStructure",
          "@type": "m2:Hierarchy",
          "rdfs:label": "Periodic Grid Structure",
          "rdfs:comment": "Multi-level hierarchical organization: 7 periods (rows) determined by principal quantum number n, 18 groups (columns) determined by valence electron configuration, 4 orbital blocks (s, p, d, f) determined by angular momentum quantum number l. The structure encodes the Aufbau principle (orbital filling order) and Pauli exclusion principle (no two electrons with identical quantum numbers).",
          "m0:subComponents": [
            "7 Periods (Period 1: H-He, Period 2: Li-Ne, ..., Period 7: Fr-Og)",
            "18 Groups (Group 1: alkali metals, Group 2: alkaline earth, ..., Group 18: noble gases)",
            "4 Blocks (s: 2 elements/period, p: 6 elements, d: 10 elements, f: 14 elements)"
          ],
          "asfidContribution": {
            "A": 0.80,
            "S": 0.95,
            "F": 0.60,
            "I": 0.85,
            "D": 0.55
          }
        },
        {
          "@id": "m0:Ptoe:ElectronConfiguration",
          "@type": "m2:Signature",
          "rdfs:label": "Electron Configuration Encoding",
          "rdfs:comment": "Each element's unique electron configuration ([core] ns^a np^b nd^c nf^d) serves as its quantum mechanical 'genotype' from which chemical properties (phenotype) emerge. Configuration determines valence electrons, oxidation states, bonding capacity, and position in the table. Governed by quantum numbers: n (shell), l (subshell), m (orbital), s (spin).",
          "m0:notation": "Spectroscopic notation (1s² 2s² 2p⁶...) or noble gas core notation ([Ne] 3s¹)",
          "m0:examples": [
            "H: 1s¹ (simplest)",
            "Ne: 1s² 2s² 2p⁶ (filled shell, noble gas)",
            "Fe: [Ar] 3d⁶ 4s² (transition metal, multiple oxidation states)",
            "U: [Rn] 5f³ 6d¹ 7s² (actinide, radioactive)"
          ],
          "asfidContribution": {
            "A": 0.85,
            "S": 0.85,
            "F": 0.60,
            "I": 0.98,
            "D": 0.55
          }
        },
        {
          "@id": "m0:Ptoe:PropertyGradients",
          "@type": "m2:Gradient",
          "rdfs:label": "Periodic Property Gradients",
          "rdfs:comment": "Directional trends in atomic properties across the table: electronegativity increases left→right and bottom→top (F=3.98 highest, Cs=0.79 lowest), atomic radius decreases left→right (shielding effect), increases top→bottom (shell addition), ionization energy increases toward noble gases, metallic character decreases left→right. These gradients encode 'potential flows' that manifest in chemical reactivity.",
          "m0:gradientTypes": [
            "∇χ (electronegativity): F > O > N > Cl > ... > Cs",
            "∇r (atomic radius): Fr > Cs > Rb > ... > He",
            "∇IE (ionization energy): He > Ne > F > ... > Cs",
            "∇EA (electron affinity): Cl > F > O > ... (less systematic)",
            "∇metallic (metallic character): Cs > ... > C > ... > F (none)"
          ],
          "asfidContribution": {
            "A": 0.70,
            "S": 0.80,
            "F": 0.85,
            "I": 0.90,
            "D": 0.60
          }
        },
        {
          "@id": "m0:Ptoe:NobleGasAttractors",
          "@type": "m2:Threshold",
          "rdfs:label": "Noble Gas Configurations as Stability Attractors",
          "rdfs:comment": "Filled electron shells (He: 1s², Ne: [He] 2s² 2p⁶, Ar: [Ne] 3s² 3p⁶, etc.) represent local energy minima and maximum stability. Neighboring elements 'attract toward' these configurations through ionization (alkali metals lose 1e⁻) or electron gain (halogens gain 1e⁻). Noble gases are chemically inert (very high ionization energy, near-zero electron affinity).",
          "m0:attractorSet": [
            "He (Z=2): 1s² (duet rule)",
            "Ne (Z=10): [He] 2s² 2p⁶ (octet rule)",
            "Ar (Z=18): [Ne] 3s² 3p⁶",
            "Kr (Z=36): [Ar] 3d¹⁰ 4s² 4p⁶",
            "Xe (Z=54): [Kr] 4d¹⁰ 5s² 5p⁶",
            "Rn (Z=86): [Xe] 4f¹⁴ 5d¹⁰ 6s² 6p⁶",
            "Og (Z=118): [Rn] 5f¹⁴ 6d¹⁰ 7s² 7p⁶ (predicted)"
          ],
          "asfidContribution": {
            "A": 0.95,
            "S": 0.80,
            "F": 0.65,
            "I": 0.85,
            "D": 0.55
          }
        },
        {
          "@id": "m0:Ptoe:QuantumConstraints",
          "@type": "m2:Constraint",
          "rdfs:label": "Quantum Mechanical Constraints",
          "rdfs:comment": "Fundamental rules governing electron configuration and table structure: (1) Pauli Exclusion Principle - no two electrons can have identical quantum numbers (n, l, m, s), limiting each orbital to 2 electrons; (2) Aufbau Principle - electrons fill orbitals in order of increasing energy (1s < 2s < 2p < 3s < 3p < 4s < 3d...); (3) Hund's Rule - electrons occupy degenerate orbitals singly before pairing.",
          "m0:constraintSet": [
            "Pauli Exclusion: max 2e⁻ per orbital (opposite spins)",
            "Aufbau: fill lowest energy orbitals first",
            "Hund: maximize unpaired electrons in degenerate orbitals",
            "2n² rule: shell capacity (K=2, L=8, M=18, N=32...)"
          ],
          "asfidContribution": {
            "A": 0.80,
            "S": 0.95,
            "F": 0.55,
            "I": 0.90,
            "D": 0.60
          }
        }
      ],
      "process": {
        "@id": "m0:Ptoe:PeriodicEmergence",
        "@type": "m2:Pattern",
        "rdfs:label": "Periodic Emergence of Chemical Properties",
        "rdfs:comment": "The process by which chemical properties emerge from atomic structure and repeat periodically. As atomic number Z increases, electrons fill orbitals following quantum rules, producing regular oscillations in properties (electronegativity, radius, reactivity). Each period ends with a noble gas (filled shell), after which the pattern repeats at the next shell level. This is not a temporal process but a structural emergence pattern encoded in the table's topology.",
        "m0:mechanism": "Quantum mechanical orbital filling (Aufbau) → Electron configuration → Valence electron count → Chemical properties → Periodic repetition every 2, 8, 8, 18, 18, 32, 32 elements (following 2n² shell capacity)",
        "m0:emergentProperties": [
          "Chemical reactivity (alkali metals highly reactive, noble gases inert)",
          "Metallic character (metals on left, nonmetals on right, metalloids diagonal boundary)",
          "Bonding behavior (ionic, covalent, metallic)",
          "Color, magnetism, conductivity (emergent from electronic structure)"
        ],
        "asfidContribution": {
          "A": 0.85,
          "S": 0.90,
          "F": 0.70,
          "I": 0.95,
          "D": 0.65
        }
      },
      "territorySpace": {
        "@id": "m0:Ptoe:TerritorySpace",
        "@type": "m3:eagle_eye:ASFID",
        "rdfs:label": "ASFID Territory (Eagle Eye 🦅)",
        "rdfs:comment": "Eagle Eye perspective measures the Periodic Table as observable phenomenon in chemical reality. The table is a static organizational structure (S dominant) encoding high-density information (I dominant) about element properties. Attractors (A) manifest as noble gas configurations. Flow (F) appears as property gradients. Dynamics (D) is limited to radioactive decay and phase transitions.",
        "stateVector": [0.85, 0.90, 0.70, 0.95, 0.65],
        "norm": 0.81,
        "normCalculation": "(0.85 + 0.90 + 0.70 + 0.95 + 0.65) / 5 = 0.81",
        "dimensionAnalysis": {
          "A_Attractor": {
            "score": 0.85,
            "justification": "Noble gas configurations (He, Ne, Ar, Kr, Xe, Rn, Og) are archetypal attractors - stable filled-shell states toward which neighboring elements converge through ionization/electron gain. Alkali metals (Group 1) readily lose 1e⁻ to reach noble gas configuration; halogens (Group 17) readily gain 1e⁻. Attractors are discrete (7 noble gases) and well-defined. Score not 1.0 because transition metals have complex multi-attractor landscapes (multiple oxidation states)."
          },
          "S_Structure": {
            "score": 0.90,
            "justification": "Exceptional structural organization: (1) 7 periods (horizontal rows) determined by principal quantum number n; (2) 18 groups (vertical columns) determined by valence configuration; (3) 4 blocks (s, p, d, f) determined by orbital angular momentum l; (4) Hierarchical nesting (periods ⊃ blocks ⊃ groups ⊃ elements). Topology is rectangular grid with 'cuts' (lanthanides/actinides separated for compactness). Symmetries include periodic repetition (2n² rule) and diagonal relationships (Li-Mg, Be-Al). Structure is immutable (fixed by quantum mechanics)."
          },
          "F_Flow": {
            "score": 0.70,
            "justification": "No intrinsic material/energy flow in the table itself (static catalog), but strong gradient flows encode directional tendencies: (1) Electronegativity gradient ∇χ (F=3.98 → Cs=0.79); (2) Atomic radius gradient ∇r; (3) Ionization energy gradient ∇IE; (4) Metallic character gradient. These gradients represent 'potential flow' that manifests when elements interact chemically. Physical flows are secondary: phase transitions at STP (gases H/N/O, liquids Hg/Br, solids most), radioactive decay (actinides, superheavy elements). Score 0.70 reflects latent/encoded flow rather than enacted flow."
          },
          "I_Information": {
            "score": 0.95,
            "justification": "Exceptionally high information density: (1) Atomic number Z as primary key (bijective with element identity); (2) Chemical symbol as semantic compression (H, He, Li... - universal alphabet); (3) Electron configuration as 'genotype' encoding; (4) Position in table deterministically predicts 10-15 properties (valence, oxidation states, reactivity, bonding, phase at STP). Mendeleev's 1869 table predicted Ga, Sc, Ge before discovery - information anticipated reality. Each cell encodes ~15 distinct measurable quantities. Information is highly structured (not random) and decodable (anyone can read properties from position)."
          },
          "D_Dynamics": {
            "score": 0.65,
            "justification": "The table itself is structurally static (no feedback loops, no self-modification), but dynamics manifest in three ways: (1) Intrinsic element dynamics - radioactive decay (U-238 → Th-234 + α, half-life 4.5 Gy), nuclear synthesis in stars (r-process, s-process), electron transitions (spectral lines); (2) Emergent interaction dynamics - chemical reactions (redox, substitution), phase transitions (melting, boiling, sublimation); (3) Historical dynamics - discovery timeline 1669 (P) to 2016 (Og), synthesis of transuranic elements (Z > 92). Score 0.65 reflects that dynamics are external to table's organizational logic, not intrinsic to the structure. Could justify 0.75 if modeling table-as-discovery-process."
          }
        }
      },
      "mapSpace": {
        "@id": "m0:Ptoe:MapSpace",
        "@type": "m3:sphinx_eye:REVOI",
        "rdfs:label": "REVOI Map Quality (Sphinx Eye 🦁)",
        "rdfs:comment": "Sphinx Eye evaluates how well the Periodic Table functions as a conceptual map of chemical reality. The table achieves exceptional scores across all REVOI dimensions: near-perfect Representability (R=0.95) via universal chemical notation, high Evolvability (E=0.80) demonstrated by 55 element additions since 1869, exceptional Verifiability (V=0.95) through spectroscopic/chemical tests, strong Observability (O=0.90) of most element properties, and high Interoperability (I=0.85) across chemistry/physics/materials science disciplines.",
        "reviStateVector": [0.95, 0.80, 0.95, 0.90, 0.85],
        "reviNorm": 0.89,
        "reviNormCalculation": "(0.95 + 0.80 + 0.95 + 0.90 + 0.85) / 5 = 0.89"
      },
      "revoi": {
        "R_Representability": {
          "score": 0.95,
          "analysis": "The Periodic Table is one of the most representable systems in all of science. (1) Visual formats: 2D grid, 3D spirals (Janet, Benfey), left-step table, circular variants; (2) Notation universality: Chemical symbols (H, C, N, O) identical across all languages; (3) Mathematical encoding: Z (atomic number) as index, (n,l,m,s) quantum numbers, periodic functions χ(Z), r(Z), IE(Z); (4) Ontological representation: JSON-LD, RDF, SPARQL-queryable databases (PubChem, ChEBI); (5) Cross-cultural stability: Symbol system unchanged since 19th century. Score 0.95 not 1.0 because lanthanides/actinides create representational density challenges in 2D (visually crowded, hard to distinguish similar properties)."
        },
        "E_Evolvability": {
          "score": 0.80,
          "analysis": "The table has proven remarkably evolvable across 150+ years: (1) Historical extensions: Mendeleev 1869 (63 elements) → Modern (118 elements) = 55 additions; (2) Conceptual refinements: Pre-quantum (empirical mass ordering) → Quantum (electron configuration basis) → Relativistic (actinide contraction, superheavy elements); (3) Layout variations: Janet left-step table (1928), Benfey spiral (1964) - structural plasticity without breaking core logic; (4) Data integration: Revised atomic weights (IUPAC biennial updates), new isotope discoveries; (5) Forward extensibility: IUPAC provisional naming for elements 119-120 (Uue, Ubn) - framework ready for expansion. Score 0.80 not higher because core structure (periods/groups/blocks) is fixed by quantum mechanics - limited parametric tunability compared to engineered systems."
        },
        "V_Verifiability": {
          "score": 0.95,
          "analysis": "Ptoe's predictions are exceptionally falsifiable (Popperian epistemology): (1) Spectroscopic verification: Each element has unique emission/absorption spectrum (atomic fingerprint) - observable via flame test, arc emission, absorption spectroscopy; (2) Mass spectrometry: Precise measurement of atomic/isotopic masses confirms Z assignment; (3) X-ray crystallography: Electronic structure validation via scattering patterns; (4) Chemical reactivity: Predicted oxidation states, bond formation experimentally confirmable (e.g., Na + Cl → NaCl, Fe exhibits +2/+3 states); (5) Historical validation: Mendeleev's predictions (Ga 1871→1875, Sc, Ge) verified before discovery. Falsifiability: Anomalies (noble gas compounds discovered 1962) forced refinement of 'inert gas' assumption. Score 0.95 not 1.0 because superheavy elements (Z > 110) have half-lives < 1s - limited bulk property measurement (observe decay products only)."
        },
        "O_Observability": {
          "score": 0.90,
          "analysis": "Most element properties are directly observable with appropriate instrumentation: (1) Atomic number Z: X-ray spectroscopy (Moseley's law K_α ∝ √(Z-1)); (2) Mass: Mass spectrometry with isotope resolution; (3) Electron configuration: Photoelectron spectroscopy (PES), X-ray absorption fine structure (XAFS); (4) Chemical properties: Reactivity assays (oxidation-reduction titrations), solubility tests; (5) Physical properties: Melting/boiling points (calorimetry), density (pycnometry), color (spectrophotometry), magnetism (SQUID), conductivity (four-point probe); (6) Emergent trends: Plot IE vs Z → observe periodic oscillation, measure χ across periods → see gradient. Limitations: (a) Some properties calculated not measured (electron affinity EA for some elements - indirect); (b) Superheavy elements (Z > 100): Observe decay products, extrapolate bulk properties. Score 0.90 reflects high but not universal direct measurability."
        },
        "I_Interoperability": {
          "score": 0.85,
          "analysis": "The Periodic Table interfaces seamlessly across multiple disciplines and notational systems: (1) Disciplinary interoperability: Chemistry (Mendeleev table, IUPAC nomenclature), Physics (quantum mechanics, nuclear shell model), Materials Science (crystal structures, band theory), Biology (biologically essential elements C/H/N/O/P/S), Geology (geochemistry, isotope ratios), Astrophysics (nucleosynthesis: Big Bang H/He, stars C/O/Fe, supernovae heavy elements); (2) Cross-notation translation: Chemical symbol ↔ Atomic number ↔ Electron configuration ↔ IUPAC name ↔ CAS registry number ↔ PubChem CID; (3) Computational interoperability: RDF/OWL ontologies (ChEBI, PubChem), SMILES/InChI encodings for compounds, SPARQL queries; (4) Standards compliance: IUPAC Gold Book definitions, NIST atomic spectra database. Score 0.85 not higher because some domain encodings are lossy (reducing Pt to 'transition metal' loses 5d⁹ 6s¹ configuration nuances; geochemistry often uses isotope-specific notation 238U vs chemistry's generic U)."
        }
      },
      "epistemicGap": {
        "@id": "m0:Ptoe:EpistemicGap",
        "rdfs:comment": "Epistemic gap δ₁ measures the normalized vectorial distance between ASFID (Territory/Eagle Eye) and REVOI (Map/Sphinx Eye) score vectors. Smaller gap indicates better framework maturity and alignment between observable reality and conceptual representation.",
        "formula": "δ₁ = ||ASFID_mean - REVOI_mean|| / √2",
        "deltaVector": [
          -0.10,
          0.10,
          -0.25,
          0.00,
          -0.20
        ],
        "deltaVectorCalculation": "REVOI - ASFID = [0.95-0.85, 0.80-0.90, 0.95-0.70, 0.90-0.95, 0.85-0.65] = [-0.10, 0.10, -0.25, 0.00, -0.20]",
        "norm": 0.057,
        "normCalculation": "||0.81 - 0.89|| / √2 = 0.08 / 1.414 ≈ 0.057",
        "spectralClass": "OnCriticalLine",
        "spectralClassRange": "[0.05, 0.15)",
        "interpretation": "δ₁ ≈ 0.057 places Ptoe in the OnCriticalLine spectral class, indicating productive tension between Territory and Map. The gap is small (high alignment) but non-zero, reflecting: (1) REVOI exceeds ASFID in Representability (R-A = +0.10) and Verifiability (V-F = +0.25) - the map is highly encodable and testable; (2) ASFID exceeds REVOI in Structure (S-E = +0.10) and Dynamics (D-I_revoi = -0.20) - the territory has richer structural organization than the map captures evolutionarily, and observed dynamics (radioactivity, phase transitions) slightly exceed the map's interoperability with dynamic frameworks. (3) Information/Observability are aligned (I-O = 0.00) - perfect information-observation symmetry. This is a healthy epistemic configuration for a mature scientific framework."
      },
